Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Paraxial Ray Diagram", "Section",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.981540268162135*^9, 
  3.9815402730946617`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"ce2ffd25-89aa-4268-8386-\
e316bddfaecd"],

Cell["\<\
An equivalent and more physically accurate way to generate ray diagrams is to \
work directly with the paraxial differential equation, rather than with \
transfer matrices.

In this approach, each lens is represented by an axial field profile, \
centered at a specific axial position. A complete optical column is then \
constructed by superposing multiple fields along the optical axis.\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.981540283028865*^9, 3.981540299465721*^9}, {
  3.981541521036606*^9, 
  3.981541521819499*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"da882ad9-fe5d-4db5-be5e-\
0790676094a0"],

Cell["\<\
Each individual field contributes locally to focusing or defocusing.\
\>", "Item",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.9785371574952793`*^9, 
  3.9785371638031187`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"8194cf21-cf4b-4060-a85f-\
d38286762046"],

Cell["Free-space regions arise naturally where the fields vanish.", "Item",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.9785371574952793`*^9, 
  3.978537166534808*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"7620f7ce-5e43-4c8e-80c3-\
e4b4bb40c930"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["\<\
The ray trajectory is obtained as a continuous solution of the paraxial ODE, \
rather than as a sequence of discrete matrix multiplications.\
\>", "Item",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.9785371574952793`*^9, 
  3.978537166209196*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"cb4a2c4b-39fa-4fad-97ab-\
4f9a4e60876f"],

